To the Dispute Resolution Department:

Under the Fair Credit Reporting Act, 15 U.S.C. §1681c(a), a consumer
reporting agency may not report most adverse items more than seven (7)
years from the date of the original delinquency that led to the
action. The narrow exceptions in §1681c(a) and (b) do not apply to
the above-referenced item.

{% if collection and collection.last_activity_date %}The last activity on this account was {{ collection.last_activity_date }}. The seven-year window for adverse reporting closed approximately on
{% if finding and finding.evidence.get('seven_year_expiry') %}{{ finding.evidence['seven_year_expiry'] }}{% else %}seven years from that date{% endif %}.
{% endif %}

I am demanding that you:

  1. Delete this item from my consumer file in its entirety —
     not simply mark it "obsolete" or "expired."
  2. Notify each furnisher that contributed to this entry of the
     deletion.
  3. Send me written confirmation that the deletion has been
     completed, identifying the date the entry was removed.

If you contend that the seven-year period has not yet expired, you
must provide me with the date of original delinquency you are using
and an explanation of how that date complies with §1681c(c) (which
fixes the date by reference to the events at §1681c(c)(1)).

I expect a written response within the 30-day window of §1681i(a)(1).
If the item remains on my file after that window, I reserve all
remedies available under §1681n and §1681o.

Sincerely,


{{ profile.name }}
